<h2 id="iterated-functions">Iterated functions</h2>

<p>The iteration of a function \(f^n\) is defined as:</p>

<p>\[f^0 = id\]
\[f^n = f \circ f^{n-1}\]</p>

<p>For example, \((x \mapsto 2x)^n = x \mapsto 2^n x\).</p>

<p>Most functions aren‚Äôt all that interesting when iterated. \(x^2\) goes to \(0\), \(1\) or \(\infty\) depending on starting point, \(\sin\) goes to 0, \(\cos\) goes to something close to <a href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=cos+x+%3D+x">0.739</a>. \(\frac{1}{x}\) has no well defined iteration, as \((x \to x^{-1})^n = x \to x^{(-1)^n}\) which does not converge.</p>

